Sections "COLLECTION" contain missmatched items: {'COLLECTION_SUMMARY': ["When the mares reached approximately 280 days of gestation (placentitis group: 279.83 ± 1.86; range: 277–282 days; control group: 280 days), they were assigned to two experimental groups. The placentitis group (n = 6) and the control group (n = 5). The mares in the placentitis group were inoculated intracervically with 1 × 106 CFU of Strep. zoo diluted in 0.5 mL of Todd-Hewitt broth, using an artificial insemination pipette to experimentally induce ascending placentitis. Before inoculation, the mares' perineal region was aseptically cleaned. The mares in the control group received no treatment. All the mares were evaluated daily by transrectal ultrasonography to assess the combined thickness of the uterus and placenta (CTUP), which allows for the diagnosis of inflammatory tissue swelling and placental separation that are typical for placentitis. Eight days after bacterial inoculation, the mares in the placentitis group presented placental separation and increased CTUP upon ultrasound imaging, while no significant change in CTUP was observed in the mares in the control group. The mares in both groups were euthanized following the American Veterinary Medical Association (AVMA) guidelines using an overdose of sodium pentobarbital at corresponding gestational ages. The uteroplacental unit was retrieved immediately after euthanasia. Amniotic fluid was collected using a syringe and needle, taking care to avoid contamination with allantoic fluid. Samples were aliquoted into cryovials and stored at −80 ºC until analysis.", "When the mares reached approximately 280 days of gestation (placentitis group: 279.83 ± 1.86; range: 277–282 days; control group: 280 days), they were assigned to two experimental groups. The placentitis group (n = 6) and the control group (n = 5). The mares in the placentitis group were inoculated intracervically with 1 × 106 CFU of Strep. zoo diluted in 0.5 mL of Todd-Hewitt broth, using an artificial insemination pipette to experimentally induce ascending placentitis. Before inoculation, the mares'' perineal region was aseptically cleaned. The mares in the control group received no treatment. All the mares were evaluated daily by transrectal ultrasonography to assess the combined thickness of the uterus and placenta (CTUP), which allows for the diagnosis of inflammatory tissue swelling and placental separation that are typical for placentitis. Eight days after bacterial inoculation, the mares in the placentitis group presented placental separation and increased CTUP upon ultrasound imaging, while no significant change in CTUP was observed in the mares in the control group. The mares in both groups were euthanized following the American Veterinary Medical Association (AVMA) guidelines using an overdose of sodium pentobarbital at corresponding gestational ages. The uteroplacental unit was retrieved immediately after euthanasia. Amniotic fluid was collected using a syringe and needle, taking care to avoid contamination with allantoic fluid. Samples were aliquoted into cryovials and stored at −80 ºC until analysis."]}